'''Diogo Meireles da Costa''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit (Portugal)|ComM]]}} ({{IPA|pt-PT|diˈoɣu ˈkɔʃtɐ}}; born 19 September 1999) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Primeira Liga]] club [[FC Porto|Porto]], which he [[Captain (association football)|captain]]s. Born in Switzerland, he represents the [[Portugal national football team|Portugal national team]]. 

Coming through [[FC Porto Juniors|Porto's youth system]], Costa won the [[UEFA Youth League]] in [[2018–19 UEFA Youth League|2019]]. He was promoted from the [[FC Porto B|reserve side]] to the first-team in 2019, winning a [[Double (association football)|domestic double]] of the [[Primeira Liga]] and the [[Taça de Portugal]] in his [[2019–20 FC Porto season|first season]]. He broke into the starting line-up in 2021, aged 22, helping Porto to a second domestic double. After [[Pepe (footballer, born 1983)|Pepe]]'s retirement in July 2024, he took up the role of captain, guiding Porto to a another league title in [[2025–26 Primeira Liga|2025–26]]. In total with Porto, Costa has won three Primeira Liga titles, four Taças de Portugal, one [[Taça da Liga]], and holds the most clean sheets in a single season, with 21 in the 2025–26 campaign. 

Costa represented Portugal at various [[Portugal national youth football team|youth levels]], being part of [[Portugal national under-17 football team|the under-17 team]] that won the [[UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2016 European Championship]], the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19 team]] that won the [[2018 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2018 European Championship]] and the [[Portugal national under-21 football team|under-21 team]] that finished as runners-up at the [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2021 European Championship]]. He made his senior international debut in 2021, and subsequently became first-choice goalkeeper, replacing Portugal's long-term option [[Rui Patrício]]. Over the following years, he represented Portugal at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024]]. He also won the [[UEFA Nations League]] in [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League|2025]].

==Club career==
===Early career===
Born in [[Rothrist]], [[Canton of Aargau]], Switzerland to [[Portuguese people|Portuguese parents]],<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Ideas |first=Think Football |date=2024-07-09 |title=8 Amazing Diogo Costa Facts From Childhood and Career Milestones |url=https://www.thinkfootballideas.co.uk/post/8-amazing-diogo-costa-facts-from-childhood-and-career-milestones#google_vignette |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Think Football Ideas |language=en}}</ref> Costa relocated to [[Santo Tirso]] in Portugal at the age of 7 due to his father gaining employment at the local [[Toilet Duck]] factory there.<ref name=Newcomer>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcporto.pt/pt/noticias/20180929-pt-atleta-revelacao-do-ano-diogo-costa |title=Atleta revelação do ano: Diogo Costa |trans-title=Newcomer athlete of the year: Diogo Costa |publisher=FC Porto |language=Portuguese |date=29 September 2018 |accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref> In his childhood, he played football with his cousin Vitor, with their idol being [[FC Porto]] legend [[Vítor Baía]], whom they looked to emulate. He started playing football at a local academy, AMCH Ringe, and later began going through some training sessions with [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]], being integrated into one of their feeder club, Póvoa de Lanhoso, where he stayed for two years, standing out alongside future teammate [[Vitinha (footballer, born February 2000)|Vitinha]], before joining FC Porto's academy in 2011, following the consent of his parents.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/reportagem/liga/diogo-costa-o-bom-gigante-que-o-fc-porto-viu-numa-casa-do-benfica |title=Diogo Costa: o bom gigante que o FC Porto viu numa Casa do Benfica |trans-title=Diogo Costa: the good giant FC Porto saw in a Benfica House |publisher=Mais Futebol |first=Pedro Jorge |last=Da Cunha |language=Portuguese |date=15 November 2019 |accessdate=26 July 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Diogo Costa: o bom gigante que o FC Porto viu numa Casa do Benfica |trans-title=Diogo Costa: the gentle giant that FC Porto spotted at a Benfica Academy. |url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/reportagem/liga/diogo-costa-o-bom-gigante-que-o-fc-porto-viu-numa-casa-do-benfica#goog_rewarded |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Maisfutebol |language=en}}</ref>

===Porto===
====2017–2021: Youth career and reserves====
Costa made his senior debut with [[FC Porto B|the reserve team]] on 6 August 2017,<ref name=":4" /> in a 1–2 home loss against [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]] for the [[LigaPro]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dn.pt/lusa/interior/comentario-gil-vicente-estreou-se-com-vitoria-em-casa-do-fc-porto-b-8688669.html |title=COMENTÁRIO: Gil Vicente estreou-se com vitória em casa do FC Porto B |trans-title=COMMENT: Gil Vicente had winning debut at FC Porto B |newspaper=[[Diário de Notícias]] |language=Portuguese |date=6 August 2017 |accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref> He finished [[2017–18 LigaPro|the season]] with a further 31 appearances, helping to a seventh-place finish, and on 15 May he renewed his contract until June 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/primeira-liga/artigos/diogo-costa-prolonga-contrato-com-o-fc-porto-ate-202122 |title=Diogo Costa prolonga contrato com o FC Porto até 2021/22 |trans-title=Diogo Costa extends contract with FC Porto until 2021/22 |publisher=SAPO |language=Portuguese |date=15 May 2018 |accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref> In September, he was named the club's Newcomer of the Year;<ref name="Newcomer" /> late in the same year, Spanish goalkeeper [[Iker Casillas]] – who started for the first team – heaped praise upon him, regarding him as his "successor".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/casillas-elege-sucessor-vai-ser-um-craque-10316558.html |title=Casillas elege sucessor na baliza do FC Porto: "Vem aí um craque" |trans-title=Casillas chooses successor in goal of FC Porto: "A star is coming" |newspaper=[[O Jogo]] |first=Carlos |last=Gouveia |language=Portuguese |date=13 December 2018 |accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref>

Costa won the [[2018–19 UEFA Youth League]] with Porto, defeating [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 3–1 in the final in [[Nyon]], Switzerland on 29 April.<ref name=Youth>{{cite news |url=https://www.dn.pt/desportos/interior/fc-porto-e-campeao-europeu-sub-19-10845534.html |title=FC Porto é campeão Europeu Sub-19 |trans-title=FC Porto are Under-19 European champions |newspaper=Diário de Notícias |last=Almeida |first=Isaura |language=Portuguese |date=29 April 2019 |accessdate=1 May 2019 |archive-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430174840/https://www.dn.pt/desportos/interior/fc-porto-e-campeao-europeu-sub-19-10845534.html |url-status=dead}}</ref> Days later, after Casillas suffered a heart attack, [[Vaná]] replaced him as starting goalkeeper and Costa was called up to the bench for the final three games of [[2018–19 Primeira Liga|the season]], starting with a 4–0 win at [[C.D. Aves|Desportivo das Aves]] on 4 May.<ref name=":2">{{cite web |url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/primeira-liga/artigos/vana-sera-titular-frente-ao-desportivo-das-aves-escreve-jornal |title=Vaná será titular frente ao Desportivo das Aves, escreve jornal |trans-title=Vaná will be starter against Desportivo das Aves, newspaper writes |publisher=SAPO |language=Portuguese |date=2 May 2019 |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{cite web |url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/fc-porto/vana-alves/vana-substituiu-casillas-e-foi-assim-a-estreia-a-titular-na-liga |title=Vaná substituiu Casillas e foi assim a estreia a titular na Liga |trans-title=Vaná replaced Casillas and that was how his starting League debut happened |publisher=Mais Futebol |language=Portuguese |date=5 May 2019 |accessdate=25 July 2020}}</ref>

[[File:Diogo Costa.jpg|thumb|Costa training with [[FC Porto|Porto]] in 2018|308x308px]]
On 25 September 2019, Costa made his first-team debut in the [[2019–20 Taça da Liga|opening group match]] of the [[Taça da Liga]], keeping a [[Shutout#Association football|clean sheet]] in a 1–0 home victory over [[C.D. Santa Clara|Santa Clara]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/em-noite-de-estreia-pelo-fc-porto-diogo-costa-recebeu-bencao-de-marchesin-11340670.html |title=Em noite de estreia pelo FC Porto, Diogo Costa recebeu bênção de Marchesín |trans-title=On the night of his debut for FC Porto, Diogo Costa received Marchesín's blessing |newspaper=O Jogo |language=Portuguese |date=26 September 2019 |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> His first [[Primeira Liga]] appearance took place on 10 November in a 1–0 away defeat of [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]], as the habitual starter [[Agustín Marchesín]] was suspended internally after a breach of discipline.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dn.pt/desportos/dragoes-com-diogo-costa-loum-marega-e-fabio-silva-no-onze-para-o-derbi-11499515.html |title=Dragão resolveu muitos problemas só com uma bomba |trans-title=Dragon took care of many problems with one rocket alone |newspaper=Diário de Notícias |first=Carlos |last=Nogueira |language=Portuguese |date=10 November 2019 |accessdate=25 July 2020}}</ref> He made a further two until the end of [[2019–20 Primeira Liga|the campaign]] for the eventual champions,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/diogo-costa-fez-historia-em-coimbra-uma-taca-de-muito-sacrificio-e-muito-trabalho-12490349.html |title=Diogo Costa fez história em Coimbra: "Uma Taça de muito sacrifício e muito trabalho" |trans-title=Diogo Costa made history in Coimbra: "A Cup full of sacrifice and hard work" |newspaper=O Jogo |first=Melo |last=Rosa |language=Portuguese |date=2 August 2020 |accessdate=19 January 2021}}</ref> as well as all seven [[Taça de Portugal]] matches as they [[2019–20 Taça de Portugal|secured]] the [[Double (association football)|double]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=F. C. Porto conquista a Taça de Portugal e a dobradinha |trans-title=F. C. Porto conquer Portuguese Cup and double |url=https://www.jn.pt/desporto/nulo-ao-intervalo-com-duas-expulsoes-para-o-f-c-porto-12488995.html/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241230135921/https://www.jn.pt/desporto/nulo-ao-intervalo-com-duas-expulsoes-para-o-f-c-porto-12488995.html/ |archive-date=2024-12-30 |access-date=2025-04-14 |work=Jornal de Notícias |language=pt}}</ref>

At the start of the 2020–21 season, Costa inherited Porto's 99 shirt,<ref name=":4" /> made famous by goalkeeper and club legend [[Vítor Baía]]. He remained Marchesín's backup, only appearing in one league game, and made his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut on 9 December 2020; he kept a clean sheet in a 2–0 [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]] win at [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/fc-porto/detalhe/diogo-costa-e-o-99-nas-costas-e-uma-grande-responsabilidade |title=Diogo Costa e o '99' nas costas: "É uma grande responsabilidade» |trans-title=Diogo Costa and the '99' on his back: «It's a big responsibility" |newspaper=[[Record (Portuguese newspaper)|Record]] |language=Portuguese |date=9 December 2020 |accessdate=10 November 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2029459--olympiacos-vs-porto/ |title=[Match report] Olympiakos vs Porto – UEFA Champions League – 2020–21 |publisher=[[UEFA]] |date=9 December 2020 |accessdate=10 November 2021}}</ref>

====2021–2023: First-choice goalkeeper and second league title====
At the start of the [[2021–22 Primeira Liga|2021–22 season]], Costa had a run as first-choice goalkeeper when Marchesín was sidelined with an injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/taca-de-portugal/artigos/marchesin-mais-perto-de-voltar-a-baliza-do-fc-porto |title=Marchesín mais perto de voltar à baliza do FC Porto |trans-title=Marchesín closer to returning to FC Porto's goal |publisher=SAPO |language=Portuguese |date=5 October 2021 |accessdate=11 October 2021}}</ref> He was September 2021's Goalkeeper of the Month, receiving 25% of the votes while Benfica's [[Odysseas Vlachodimos]] received 22%.<ref>{{cite news |title=Diogo Costa eleito melhor guarda-redes do mês de setembro |trans-title=Diogo Costa voted best goalkeeper of the month of September |url=https://www.noticiasaominuto.com/desporto/1849308/diogo-costa-eleito-melhor-guarda-redes-do-mes-de-setembro |access-date=29 March 2022 |publisher=Notícias ao Minuto |date=11 October 2021 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> On 16 October, he agreed to a contract extension to 2026, increasing his [[buyout clause]] from €30 million to €60 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Diogo Costa, a renovação e um número especial: "É uma grande responsabilidade" |trans-title=Diogo Costa, the renewal and a special number: "It's a great responsibility" |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/diogo-costa-a-renovacao-e-um-numero-especial-e-sempre-uma-responsabilidade-14227273.html |access-date=29 March 2022 |work=O Jogo |date=16 October 2021 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> After helping Porto to an unbeaten run of sixteen consecutive league games, during which he kept eight clean sheets, he was named the league's Goalkeeper of the Month for four consecutive months from December to March 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=Diogo Costa foi novamente eleito guarda-redes do mês na Liga Bwin |trans-title=Diogo Costa was again elected goalkeeper of the month in the Liga Bwin |url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/fc-porto/detalhe/diogo-costa-foi-novamente-eleito-guarda-redes-do-mes-na-liga-bwin |access-date=29 March 2022 |work=Record |date=14 February 2022 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>

He would then be part of five more victories that would seal Porto a second [[Double (association football)|domestic double]] of the [[Primeira Liga]] and the [[Taça de Portugal]], after keeping a clean sheet in the 1–0 victory of ''[[O Clássico]]'' against rivals [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] on 7 May, and 15 days later Porto 3–1 defeating [[C.D. Tondela|Tondela]] in the [[2022 Taça de Portugal final|domestic cup final]].<ref name=":6">{{Cite web |title=Zaidu winner takes Porto to the title away to bitter rivals Benfica |url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/2577-zaidu-winner-takes-porto-to-the-title-away-to-bitter-rivals-benfica |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=portugoal.net}}</ref><ref name=":5">{{Cite web |title=Taça de Portugal Final: Porto take down Tondela to seal domestic double |url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/2599-taca-de-portugal-final-porto-take-down-tondela-to-seal-domestic-double |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=portugoal.net}}</ref> Despite finishing the season with 15 clean sheets, the [[2021–22 Primeira Liga#Clean Sheets|second-highest]] total behind [[Antonio Adán]] of [[Sporting CP]], Costa was still named in the Primeira Liga Team of the Year ahead of him.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/artigo/diogo-costa-eleito-melhor-guarda-redes-da-liga-bwin-202122/14950582 |title=Diogo Costa eleito melhor guarda-redes da Liga Bwin 2021/22 |publisher=[[O Jogo]] |date=18 June 2022 |access-date=18 June 2022}}</ref> He also named the Primeira Liga Goalkeeper of the Year, having started in 33 of 34 Porto's league matches of the season, having missed only their last match, with the title being already secured.<ref name=":0"/>

On 4 October, Costa managed to save a penalty from [[Patrik Schick]], and preserved a clean sheet in a 2–0 home win over [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] in a [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group B|Champions League group stage]] match. In the reverse fixture against them, on 12 October, Costa managed to provide an assist to a goal from [[Galeno]], then saved a penalty from [[Kerem Demirbay]], and preserved a clean sheet in a 3–0 away win against Leverkusen in Germany, becoming the first goalkeeper to achieve that feat in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/2851-porto-s-champions-league-campaign-back-on-track-after-beating-bayer-leverkusen-3-0-at-the-bayarena |title=Porto's Champions League campaign back on track after beating Bayer Leverkusen 3-0 at the BayArena |website=portugoal.net |date=12 October 2022}}</ref> On 26 October, Costa saved another penalty from [[Noa Lang]], as Porto's went on to win the game 4–0 away against [[Club Brugge KV|Club Brugge]], becoming the first goalkeeper to save three consecutive penalties in the competition's history.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Porto exact sweet revenge against Club Brugge to book last-16 Champions League berth |url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/2879-porto-exact-sweet-revenge-against-club-brugge-to-book-last-16-champions-league-berth |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=portugoal.net}}</ref> His form throughout the club's Champions League group stage campaign, saw him help his side qualify to the [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Round of 16|round of sixteen]], as group winners, following a 2–1 home win over [[Atlético Madrid]] on 1 November, amassing 43 saves, and a man of the match award, during the group stage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/2891-porto-beat-atletico-madrid-2-1-to-take-top-spot-in-the-champions-league |title=Porto beat Atlético Madrid 2-1 to take top spot in the Champions League |publisher=PortuGOAL |first=Marshall |last=Matthew |date=1 November 2022 |access-date=11 November 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/027b-168afcd10194-feff7b6315ad-1000--champions-league-fantasy-football-goalkeepers/ |title=Champions League Fantasy Football: Goalkeepers |publisher=[[UEFA]] |date=8 November 2022 |access-date=11 November 2022}}</ref>

On 28 January 2023, Costa kept a clean sheet in the [[2023 Taça da Liga final|2–0 final]] win over Sporting CP, helping Porto win their first [[Taça da Liga]] in [[Leiria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/sergio-conceicao-e-a-da-taca-da-liga-nao-faz-sentido-desvalorizar-trofeus-15741387.html |title=Sérgio Conceição e a da Taça da Liga: "Não faz sentido desvalorizar troféus" |trans-title=Sérgio Conceição and the League Cup win: "It makes no sense to devalue trophies" |newspaper=O Jogo |first=Rodrigo |last=Cortez |language=pt |date=28 January 2023 |access-date=29 January 2023}}</ref> On 22 February, in the first leg of [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League#Round-of-16|Champions League round-of-16]], Costa proved to crucial for Porto, making several crucial saves as they lost 1–0 away in the first leg, to eventual tournament runners-up [[Inter Milan]]. On 14 March, in the second leg, despite keeping a clean sheet at home, in his 100th appearance for Porto, producing several decisive saves, a 0–0 draw prevented them from advancing to the quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/it/liste/inter-porto-cronaca-tabellino-pagelle-voti/blt7ab7f2ef14f27f4d |title=Inter-Porto 1-0: Lukaku comes in and solves it, the first round is Nerazzurri |author=Marco Trombetta |website=Goal.com |date=22 February 2023 |access-date=23 February 2023 |archive-date=23 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230223082903/https://www.goal.com/it/liste/inter-porto-cronaca-tabellino-pagelle-voti/blt7ab7f2ef14f27f4d |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/it/notizie/inter-riecco-lukaku-in-goal-in-serie-a-189-giorni-dopo/bltbb980d90cb9d7e8f |title=Inter, Lukaku returns as protagonist: decisive also in the Champions League |website=Goal.com |date=22 February 2023 |access-date=23 February 2023 |archive-date=23 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230223082908/https://www.goal.com/it/notizie/inter-riecco-lukaku-in-goal-in-serie-a-189-giorni-dopo/bltbb980d90cb9d7e8f |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=SAPO |title=Diogo Costa chegou aos 100 jogos pelo FC Porto: "É um sonho tornado realidade" |url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/primeira-liga/artigos/diogo-costa-chegou-aos-100-jogos-pelo-fc-porto-e-um-sonho-tornado-realidade |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=SAPO Desporto |language=pt}}</ref> On 4 June, his team won the [[2023 Taça de Portugal final]] 2–0 against [[S.C. Braga|Braga]], with Costa keeping another clean sheet.<ref name="TP23">{{cite news |url=https://www.dn.pt/desporto/vice-rei-sergio-conceicao-levantou-a-19-taca-de-portugal-dos-dragoes-16476009.html |title=Vice-rei Sérgio Conceição levantou a 19.ª Taça de Portugal dos dragões |trans-title=Viceroy Sérgio Conceição lifted the Dragons' 19th Portuguese Cup |newspaper=Diário de Notícias |first=Isaura |last=Almeida |language=pt |date=4 June 2023 |access-date=4 June 2023}}</ref> In the league, Porto finished as runners-up, with Costa reaching 16 clean sheets goals in 33 games, contributing decisively for the club's second-best defensive record in the competition, being named for the second consecutive season the Primeira Liga Goalkeeper of the Year.<ref name="PGKS" />

====2023–Present: Club captain and individual accolades====
Over the course of the 2023 summer transfer window, there was much speculation that Costa would leave Porto with [[Chelsea F.C|Chelsea]], and [[Manchester United]] all heavily linked with the player. Porto were adamant he would not be sold for less than his €75 million release clause, leading both clubs to pull out of the deal, due to the overall cost of the transfer with United signing [[André Onana]] instead.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Man Utd 'leading race' to sign Porto goalkeeper Diogo Costa after latest high-profile David de Gea clanger |language=en |work=[[Goal.com]] |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/man-utd-leading-race-sign-porto-goalkeeper-diogo-costa-david-de-gea/bltf6b55e8b26986b1e |access-date=2024-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Holland |first=James |date=2024-05-31 |title=Chelsea overtake Man Utd, Man City in race for £65m star as contact made |url=https://www.teamtalk.com/news/chelsea-overtake-man-utd-man-city-race-65-million-star-contact-made |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=TEAMtalk |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Cohen |first=Mathew |date=2023-07-02 |title=Manchester United end Diogo Costa pursuit in favour of Andre Onana |url=https://thepeoplesperson.com/2023/07/02/manchester-united-end-diogo-costa-pursuit-in-favour-of-andre-onana-266094/ |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Man United News And Transfer News {{!}} The Peoples Person |language=en-US}}</ref> He was also linked to a move to [[Bayern Munich]] and [[Real Madrid]], following an injury to their starting goalkeepers, but a move never materialised, and he ended up staying at Porto for the upcoming season.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tully |first=David |date=2024-07-04 |title=Chelsea Told They Will Now Have To Pay £63.5M For Player After "Brilliant" Euro 2024 Display |url=https://chelseanews.com/blog/chelsea-transfer-news-diogo-costa-3/ |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=chelseanews.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2023-08-10 |title=FC Porto Diogo Costa apontado a Real Madrid e Bayern Munique {{!}} Abola.pt |url=https://www.abola.pt/futebol/noticias/diogo-costa-apontado-a-real-madrid-e-bayern-munique-2023082911175117965 |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Abola.pt |language=pt}}</ref>

In the [[2023–24 FC Porto season|2023–24]] season, despite a third-place finish from Porto in the [[2023–24 Primeira Liga|Primeira Liga]], he ended the season with 14 clean sheets out of 34 league matches, the highest in the season. Costa also featured in the entirety of Porto's [[2024 Taça de Portugal Final|Taça de Portugal final]] victory over Sporting CP on 26 May, which ended 2–1.<ref name="Taça">{{cite web |url=https://www.rtp.pt/noticias/fc-porto/taca-de-portugal-sergio-conceicao-e-o-terceiro-treinador-a-vencer-quatro-finais_d1574481 |title=Taça de Portugal. Sérgio Conceição é o terceiro treinador a vencer quatro finais |trans-title=Portugal Cup. Sérgio Conceição is the third manager to win four finals |publisher=Rádio e Televisão de Portugal |language=pt |date=26 May 2024 |access-date=27 May 2024}}</ref> Shortly after, he was linked with a move to Saudi Arabia, with three clubs in the [[Saudi Pro League]] interested in him, as well as [[Manchester City]] as potencial replacement for [[Ederson (footballer, born 1993)|Ederson]], who was linked to a move to Saudi Pro League side [[Al-Ittihad Club (Jeddah)|Al-Ittihad]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Redação |date=2024-07-29 |title=Diogo Costa pretendido pelos sauditas e Gonçalo Borges próximo do Estrasburgo |trans-title=Diogo Costa wanted by the Saudis and Gonçalo Borges close to Strasbourg. |url=https://www.jn.pt/5096893383/diogo-costa-pretendido-pelos-sauditas-e-goncalo-borges-proximo-do-estrasburgo/ |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Jornal de Notícias |language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Al Ittihad com guarda-redes a caminho e não é Diogo Costa nem Ederson |trans-title=Al Ittihad with a goalkeeper on the way, and it's not Diogo Costa or Ederson. |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/2626653378/al-ittihad-com-guarda-redes-a-caminho-e-nao-e-diogo-costa-nem-ederson/ |access-date=2024-10-12 |work=O Jogo |language=pt}}</ref> However, on 2 July, Porto's President [[André Villas-Boas]] confirmed that the club was not willing to sell him, as he was "one of their biggest assets".<ref>{{Cite news |title=FC Porto quer segurar Diogo Costa: "Não temos interesse em vermo-nos livres dele" |trans-title=FC Porto wants to keep Diogo Costa: "We have no interest in getting rid of him" |url=https://sicnoticias.pt/desporto/2024-07-02-video-fc-porto-quer-segurar-diogo-costa-nao-temos-interesse-em-vermo-nos-livres-dele-3bb5dae0 |access-date=2024-10-12 |work=[[SIC Notícias]] |language=pt}}</ref>

[[File:FC Salzburg gegen FC Porto (2025-09-25 UEFA Euro League ) 77.jpg|thumb|Costa with Porto during the 2025–26 season|333x333px]]
On 12 July, it was announced that Costa would become the new [[Captain (association football)|club captain]] following [[Pepe (footballer, born 1983)|Pepe]]'s retirement and [[Iván Marcano]] long-term injury, with new vice-captains being [[Cláudio Ramos (footballer)|Cláudio Ramos]] and [[Fábio Cardoso]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Abola.pt |date=2024-07-12 |title=Quadro de capitães do FC Porto ganha forma {{!}} Abola.pt |trans-title=FC Porto's captaincy structure takes shape. |url=https://www.abola.pt/futebol/noticias/quadro-de-capitaes-do-fc-porto-ganha-forma-2024071122000572474 |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Abola.pt |language=pt}}</ref> On 3 August, he captained his side in the first competitive match of the [[2024–25 FC Porto season|season]] as Porto won the [[2024 Supertaça Cândido de Oliveira]] by defeating Sporting CP with a 4–3 victory, despite being down by three goals.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Porto pull off stunning comeback to beat Sporting in seven-goal Super Taça thriller |url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/4011-porto-star-in-seven-goal-super-taca-thriller |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=portugoal.net}}</ref> On 29 September, in a 4–0 league win against [[FC Arouca|Arouca]], Costa kept his 100th career clean sheet, at age of 25, in his 161st appearance for the club.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Diogo Costa, 100 vezes sem sofrer golos: "A fasquia está muito alta" |trans-title=Diogo Costa, 100 clean sheets: "The bar is set very high" |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/346342381/diogo-costa-100-vezes-sem-sofrer-golos-a-fasquia-esta-muito-alta/ |access-date=2024-10-31 |work=O Jogo |language=pt}}</ref> Despite a difficult start to the season for Porto defensively, after keeping three clean sheets in five league matches, he was named the Primeira Liga's Goalkeeper of the Month for September and October.<ref name="GKM">{{Cite web |date=2024-11-04 |title=Diogo Costa vence Prémio ABANCA Guarda-Redes do Mês |trans-title=Diogo Costa wins the ABANCA Goalkeeper of the Month Award. |url=https://www.ligaportugal.pt/pt/epocas/20242025/noticias/geral/premios/liga-portugal-betclic/setembrooutubro/diogo-costa-vence-premio-abanca-guarda-redes-do-mes/ |access-date=2024-11-07 |website=Liga Portugal |language=pt}}</ref> He would finish the season with the most clean sheets in the league at 16, despite Porto finishing third in the Primeira Liga.<ref>{{cite web |title=Duas épocas consecutivas no 3.º lugar: FC Porto com registo pouco habitual |url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/fc-porto/detalhe/duas-epocas-consecutivas-no-3-lugar-fc-porto-com-registo-pouco-habitual |date=15 January 2024 |access-date=15 January 2024 |website=Record |language=pt}}</ref> His performances saw him being named the league's Goalkeeper of the Season, and saw Costa being included in the season's best XI.<ref>{{cite web |title=Diogo Costa supera Anatoliy Trubin e integra Onze do Ano da I Liga |url=https://www.noticiasaominuto.com/desporto/2800146/diogo-costa-supera-anatoliy-trubin-e-integra-onze-do-ano-da-i-liga |date=12 June 2024 |access-date=14 June 2025 |website=Notícias ao Minuto |language=pt}}</ref> 

During the final days of the 2025 summer transfer window, [[Aston Villa]] considered signing Costa as a pontential replacement of [[Emiliano Martínez]]. Despite Costa not being keen on the move, the transfer collapsed due Martínez remaining at Villa, after failing to secure a move to Manchester United.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mercado: Aston Villa ataca Diogo Costa, FC Porto intransigente |url=https://www.abola.pt/noticias/mercado-aston-villa-ataca-diogo-costa-fc-porto-intransigente-2025083111595395357 |date=31 August 2025 |access-date=29 May 2026 |website=A Bola |language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pinto |first1=Vítor |last2=Monteiro |first2=André |title=Diogo Costa fechou porta ao Aston Villa |url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-betclic/fc-porto/detalhe/diogo-costa-fechou-porta-ao-aston-villa |date=2 September 2025 |access-date=29 May 2026 |website=Record |language=pt}}</ref> On 23 December, Costa extended his contract with Porto until June 2030, which saw his release clause decrease to €60 million.<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 December 2025 |title=Diogo Costa renova até 2030 |trans-title=Diogo Costa renews until 2030 |url=https://www.fcporto.pt/pt/noticias/20251223-pt-diogo-costa-renova-ate-2030 |access-date=24 December 2025 |publisher=[[FC Porto]] |language=pt}}</ref> 

On 2 May 2026, Costa guided Porto to the league title — his third with the club — keeping a clean sheet in a 1–0 win against [[F.C. Alverca|Alverca]], bringing his tally to 26 clean sheets for the campaign. That clean sheet broke the club record for the most clean sheets in a single season in the 21st century — which was previously set at 25, by both [[Sergei Ovchinnikov (footballer, born 1970)|Sergei Ovchinnikov]] in the 2000–01 season and [[Helton (footballer)|Helton]] in the 2012–13 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/fr/news/italian-coach-farioli-wins-first-league-title-with-fc-porto-42804464 |title=Italian coach Farioli wins first League title with FC Porto |publisher=OneFootball |date=2 May 2026 }}</ref> On 16 May, he broke the record for the most clean sheets in a Primeira Liga season with 21, after a 1–0 home win over Santa Clara in Porto's last league match of the season. He also extended the club's record of 27 clean sheets in all competitions and kept the most clean sheets of any goalkeeper in a Primeira Liga season for the third consecutive season. This led to him being named the league's Goalkeeper of the Year and best XI for the second consecutive season.<ref>https://www.fcporto.pt/pt/noticias/20260520-pt-diogo-costa-no-onze-do-ano-da-liga</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Costa started all of [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal]]'s matches in the [[2016 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]. In the final against [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain]], he saved [[Manu Morlanes]]' spot kick in a 5–4 penalty shoot-out victory after a 1–1 draw, helping his team win the tournament for the sixth time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/match/2019912--portugal-vs-spain/ |title=Portugal win second U17 EURO title on penalties |publisher=UEFA |date=21 May 2016 |access-date=7 June 2017}}</ref> With the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19s]], he participated in the [[2017 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2017 European Championship]], playing four out of five matches as they lost in the final to [[England national under-19 football team|England]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-07-15 |title=European Under-19 Championship: England beat Portugal in final |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40619862 |access-date=2025-04-14 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He represented [[Portugal national under-20 football team|the nation]] at the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/news/y=2017/m=5/news=dalot-targeting-back-to-back-golden-summers-2886251.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523084012/http://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/news/y=2017/m=5/news=dalot-targeting-back-to-back-golden-summers-2886251.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2017 |title=Dalot targeting back-to-back golden summers |publisher=FIFA |date=23 May 2017 |access-date=7 June 2017}}</ref> starting in all the matches in a quarter-final exit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round=275956/match=300367044/match-report.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604142900/http://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round=275956/match=300367044/match-report.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 June 2017 |title=Uruguay progress, Portugal pay the penalty |publisher=FIFA |date=4 June 2017 |access-date=7 June 2017}}</ref>

In [[2018 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|July 2018]], Costa played four matches out of five at the [[UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] in Finland, helping [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal]] win the tournament for the first time,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Esteves |first=Adérito |title=Conheça os 20 (mais um) campeões europeus de sub-19 |trans-title=Meet the 21 (plus one) under-19 European champions |url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/internacional/europeu-sub-19/conheca-os-20-mais-um-campeoes-europeus-de-sub-19 |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Maisfutebol |language=en}}</ref> but missed the final due to a muscle injury.<ref>{{Cite web |last=DN |first=Redacao |date=2018-07-27 |title=Guarda-redes de Portugal falha final do Europeu sub-19 |trans-title=Portugal goalkeeper misses under-19 European Championship final |url=https://www.dn.pt/desportos/interior/europeu-sub-19-guarda-redes-diogo-costa-substituido-por-ricardo-benjamin-9648076.html |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Diário de Notícias |language=pt}}</ref> Previously, on 25 May, the 18-year-old won his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] for the [[Portugal national under-21 football team|under-21 side]], coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 3–2 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win over [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=SAPO |title=Seleção Sub-21 de Portugal vence Itália em amigável disputado no Estoril |trans-title=Under-21 Portuguese national team beat Italy in friendly held in Estoril |url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/selecao/artigos/selecao-sub-21-de-portugal-vence-italia-em-amigavel-disputado-no-estoril |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=SAPO Desporto |language=pt}}</ref> In March 2021, Costa played all of Portugal's matches in the [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]], as Portugal finished the tournament as runners-up, losing the final 1–0 to [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Highlights, report: Germany beat Portugal for third U21 EURO title |url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/news/026a-127532d17acc-e079bf3c8a1c-1000--highlights-report-germany-beat-portugal-for-third-u21-euro-titl/ |access-date=29 March 2022 |publisher=UEFA |date=6 June 2021}}</ref>

===Senior===
Costa was called up to [[Portugal national football team|the senior team]] for the first time on 26 August 2021,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-11-25 |title=6 Facts About Portuguese Goalkeeper Diogo Costa |url=https://www.portugal.com/history-and-culture/6-facts-about-portuguese-goalkeeper-diogo-costa/ |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Portugal.com |language=en-US}}</ref> for [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifiers]] against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]] and a friendly with [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/portugal/selecao-nacional/selecao-os-convocados-de-fernando-santos |title=Seleção: os convocados de Fernando Santos |trans-title=National team: those called up by Fernando Santos |publisher=Mais Futebol |language=Portuguese |date=26 August 2021 |accessdate=27 August 2021}}</ref> He made his debut on 9 October against the last of those opponents, in a 3–0 victory at [[Algarve Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portugoal.net/selecao/2287-portugal-3-0-qatar-matheus-nunes-rafael-leao-make-their-selecao-debuts |title=Portugal 3–0 Qatar – Diogo Costa, Matheus Nunes & Rafael Leão make their Seleção debuts |publisher=PortuGOAL |date=9 October 2021 |accessdate=10 October 2021}}</ref> Costa was chosen as the first-choice goalkeeper by the head coach [[Fernando Santos (footballer, born 1954)|Fernando Santos]] for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA second round|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification play-offs]], relegating usual starter [[Rui Patrício]] to the bench.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ferreira |first1=Sébastien |title=Barrages Mondial 2022 : avec Diogo Costa, le Portugal a baptisé son nouvel ange-gardien |trans-title=2022 World Cup playoffs: in Diogo Costa, Portugal have baptised their new guardian angel |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/sports/football/coupe-du-monde/barrages-mondial-2022-avec-diogo-costa-le-portugal-a-baptise-son-nouvel-ange-gardien-20220328 |access-date=29 March 2022 |work=[[Le Figaro]] |date=28 March 2022 |language=French}}</ref> On 24 March, at his club ground, he played his first competitive game in a 3–1 win over [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] in the play-off semi-finals;<ref>{{cite news |title=Diogo Costa e a titularidade frente à Turquia: "Foi muito especial para mim" |trans-title=Diogo Costa and the starting role against Turkey: "It was very special for me" |url=https://www.record.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/mundial/mundial-2022/detalhe/diogo-costa-e-a-titularidade-frente-a-turquia-foi-muito-especial-para-mim |access-date=29 March 2022 |work=Record |date=24 March 2022 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> he featured again five days later in a 2–0 victory over [[North Macedonia national football team|North Macedonia]] that sealed a place for the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernandes |first1=Mariana |last2=Paredes |first2=Diogo |title=Portugal vence Macedónia do Norte com bis de Bruno Fernandes e está no Mundial do Qatar (2–0) – como aconteceu |trans-title=Portugal defeat North Macedonia with a brace from Bruno Fernandes and are in the World Cup in Qatar (2–0) – how it happened |url=https://observador.pt/liveblogs/portugal-macedonia-do-norte-danilo-mantem-se-a-central-ao-lado-de-pepe-diogo-costa-volta-a-ser-titular-na-baliza/ |access-date=29 March 2022 |work=Observador |date=29 March 2022 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>

[[File:DiogoCostatrainingPortugal.jpg|thumb|Costa training with [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in 2023|258x258px]]
Costa was called up for the final 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web |last=SAPO |title=Os 26 convocados de Portugal: Gonçalo Ramos, António Silva, Otávio e Matheus Nunes chamados |trans-title=Portugal select 26: Gonçalo Ramos, António Silva, Otávio and Matheus Nunes called |url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/mundial/artigos/os-26-convocados-de-portugal-para-o-mundial2022 |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=SAPO Desporto |language=pt}}</ref> On 25 November, he played his first World Cup match, a 3–2 group stage win against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]. This made him the youngest Portuguese goalkeeper to play in a major international tournament, at age 23.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Garcia |first=Adriana |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/portugal-por/story/4805137/cristiano-ronaldo-becomes-first-man-to-score-in-5-world-cups |title=Portugal's Cristiano Ronaldo becomes first male player to score in 5 World Cups |date=24 November 2022 |access-date=24 November 2022 |work=ESPN}}</ref> However, Costa had a difficult game, nearly costing his team's match in injury time. While setting the ball down on the pitch, Costa prepared to kick the ball out of the box, but he did not know that Ghana striker [[Iñaki Williams]] was lurking behind him, as Williams proceeded to charge forward and steal the ball, he ended up slipping while being challenged by Costa, leading Portugal's defence to clear the ball and seal the victory.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gavin • • |first=Mike |date=2022-11-24 |title=Portugal Goalkeeper Nearly Makes Devastating Mistake in World Cup |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/portugal-goalkeeper-nearly-makes-devastating-mistake-in-world-cup/3971193/ |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=NBC New York |language=en-US}}</ref> He still played every minute of the campaign, as they were knocked out of the tournament after losing in the quarter-finals to [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]], where he misjudged a cross when coming for the ball, and [[Youssef En-Nesyri]] headed the only goal of the game.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Glendenning |first=Barry |date=2022-12-10 |title=Morocco 1-0 Portugal: World Cup 2022 quarter-final – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2022/dec/10/morocco-portugal-world-cup-2022-quarter-final-live |access-date=2025-04-14 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> 

Despite a difficult World Cup, Costa retained his place under new manager [[Roberto Martínez]], on the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying|qualifiers]], helping Portugal keep a clean sheet in the 9–0 home defeat of [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] during the same phase on 11 September 2023, their biggest win in international history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/portugal/selecao-nacional/portugal-9-0-luxemburgo-cronica |title=Portugal 9–0 Luxemburgo (crónica) |trans-title=Portugal 9–0 Luxembourg (report) |publisher=Mais Futebol |first=Pedro |last=Lemos |language=pt |date=11 September 2023 |access-date=11 September 2023}}</ref> He finished the qualifying campaign, keeping nine clean sheets out of ten matches, only conceding two goals against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] in a 3–2 home win on 13 October, with Portugal topping their qualifying group, and setting a new national team record of 10 consecutive wins.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/0253-0d80578af302-67dcd0042fc2-1000--lukaku-sets-new-european-qualifiers-scoring-record/ |title=Lukaku sets new European Qualifiers scoring record |date=19 November 2023 |website=UEFA}}</ref> On 21 May 2024, he was selected in the 26-man squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |date=21 May 2024 |title=Convocados para o Euro 2024 |trans-title=Called up for Euro 2024 |url=https://www.fpf.pt/pt/News/Todas-as-not%C3%ADcias/Not%C3%ADcia/news/45104 |language=pt |publisher=Portuguese Football Federation |access-date=21 May 2024}}</ref> In the round of 16 match against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]], he was awarded player of the match, as he cleared a one-to-one chance from [[Benjamin Šeško]] in the extra time, before saving all three penalties in the shootout, becoming the first ever goalkeeper in the [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]] to do so, securing his country's qualification to the quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Murray |first=Scott |date=2024-07-01 |title=Portugal 0-0 Slovenia (aet; pens 3-0): Euro 2024, last 16 – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2024/jul/01/portugal-v-slovenia-euro-2024-last-16-live |access-date=2025-04-14 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b22000e24bf-9d79cc6fc92b-1000--every-euro-2024-player-of-the-match/ |title=Every EURO 2024 Player of the Match |publisher=UEFA |date=1 July 2024}}</ref> Costa recalled the match by saying it was "the best match of my life, the match in which I managed to help my team the most. I had to follow my instinct, that's what I felt. I'm very happy and very excited to help the team so much".<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-07-01 |title="Melhor jogo da minha vida": Diogo Costa "muito emocionado" por ter ajudado Portugal frente à Eslovénia |url=https://sicnoticias.pt/especiais/euro-2024/2024-07-01-video-melhor-jogo-da-minha-vida-diogo-costa-muito-emocionado-por-ter-ajudado-portugal-frente-a-eslovenia-6c651279 |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=SIC Notícias |language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=1 July 2024 |title="Foi o melhor jogo da minha vida": Diogo Costa diz que seguiu "o instinto" |trans-title="It was the best game of my life": Diogo Costa says he followed "his instinct" |url=https://cnnportugal.iol.pt/videos/foi-o-melhor-jogo-da-minha-vida-diogo-costa-diz-que-seguiu-o-instinto/66832ccb0cf2cd207b848f1f |publisher=[[CNN Portugal]]}}</ref> Portugal were eliminated in the quarter-finals to [[France national football team|France]] after losing 5–3 in another penalty shootout, with Costa failing to save any penalty.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy79llev4znt |title=Portugal 0–0 France (France win 5–3 on pens) |publisher=BBC Sport |first=Emma |last=Sanders |date=5 July 2024 |access-date=6 July 2024}}</ref>

On 20 May 2025, Costa was selected for Portugal's [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals]] [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals squads#Portugal|squad]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Convocatória para Liga das Nações divulgada |trans-title=Nations League squad announced |url=https://www.fpf.pt/pt/News/Todas-as-notícias/Notícia/news/50645 |website=[[Portuguese Football Federation]] |language=pt |access-date=26 May 2025 |date=20 May 2025}}</ref> He and his team would go on to win the tournament [[2025 UEFA Nations League final|5–3 in a penalty shootout]] over rivals [[Spain national football team|Spain]], in which he had a crucial role by saving a penalty from [[Álvaro Morata]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6408339/2025/06/08/spain-portugal-yamal-mendes-ronaldo/ |title=Spain 2 Portugal 2 (3–5 on pens): Mendes vs Yamal, Ronaldo being Ronaldo, and World Cup chances |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |first1=Tim |last1=Spiers |first2=Dermot |last2=Corrigan |first3=Stu |last3=James |date=8 June 2025 |access-date=8 June 2025}}</ref>

==Style of play==
[[File:DiogoCosta22WC.jpg|thumb|upright|Costa making a save during a [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] group stage match against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], which Portugal won 2–0|233x233px]]
Described as a "[[Goalkeeper (association football)#Sweeper-keeper|sweeper-keeper]]" because of his playing style, Costa is a goalkeeper distinguished by his technical skills and tactical intelligence. He possesses exceptional reflexes and reaction times, enabling him to execute difficult saves in one-on-one situations and against point-blank shots. Costa also excels in penalty situations, displaying composure and a strong sense of positioning. His effectiveness in collecting crosses further highlights his decision-making abilities and overall goalkeeping prowess.<ref name="SP1">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4680127/2023/07/14/diogo-costa-50-to-watch/ |title=Diogo Costa: The Casillas-endorsed goalkeeper who makes laser-guided deliveries |website=[[The Athletic]] |date=14 July 2023 |last1=Lang |first1=Jack}}</ref><ref name=":7">{{Cite web |last=Fitzgerald |first=Dan |date=2022-10-07 |title=Why Manchester United are desperate to sign FC Porto's Diogo Costa |url=https://thepeoplesperson.com/2022/10/07/why-manchester-united-are-desperate-to-sign-fc-portos-diogo-costa-253557/ |access-date=2025-04-14 |website=Man United News And Transfer News {{!}} The Peoples Person |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="SP3">{{Cite web |title=Quem é Diogo Costa? Conheça o herói da classificação de Portugal na Eurocopa |trans-title=Who is Diogo Costa? Get to know the hero of Portugal's qualification for the Euro Cup. |url=https://www.lance.com.br/futebol-internacional/quem-e-diogo-costa-conheca-o-heroi-da-classificacao-de-portugal-na-eurocopa.html |website=Lance!}}</ref>

Tactically, Costa is a goalkeeper who is comfortable with the ball at his feet, facilitating play from the back and aiding in ball distribution. His precise short and long passes help initiate attacks and maintain possession for his team. Additionally, Costa has strong game awareness and positioning, allowing him to anticipate plays and effectively intercept crosses and aerial threats. His leadership qualities are evident on the field; he communicates well with his defensive teammates, showcasing maturity and confidence in organizing the defensive line to ensure team compactness.<ref name="SP1" /><ref name=":7" /><ref name="SP3"/> Pedro Pereira, a goalkeeping coach who worked with Costa in [[FC Porto|Porto]]'s youth system and [[FC Porto B|B team]], described him as "a very calm goalkeeper, one with real presence", and stated that "he has clarity in key moments and controls his emotions very well. He exudes security in everything he does, and that transmits a sense of serenity to the team."<ref name="SP1" />

==Personal life==
Costa and his wife Catarina Machado have a son born in November 2022, named Tomás Costa.<ref>{{cite web |date=11 November 2022 |title=Diogo Costa foi pai. O primeiro filho chama-se Tomás |trans-title=Diogo Costa became a father. The first child is named Tomás. |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/area-j/excitacoes/diogo-costa-foi-pai-o-primeiro-filho-chama-se-tomas-15343582.html |access-date=12 November 2022 |publisher=[[O Jogo]]}}</ref>

